continuous-integration.md
     1Ôćĺ# Running `mdbook` in continuous integration
     3ÔćĺThere are a variety of services such as [GitHub Actions] or [GitLab CI/CD] which can be used to test and deploy your book automatically.
     4Ôćĺ
     5ÔćĺThe following provides some general guidelines on how to configure your service to run mdBook.
     6ÔćĺSpecific recipes can be found at the [Automated Deployment] wiki page.
     7Ôćĺ
     8Ôćĺ[GitHub Actions]: https://docs.github.com/en/actions
     9Ôćĺ[GitLab CI/CD]: https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/ci/
    10Ôćĺ[Automated Deployment]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/wiki/Automated-Deployment
    11Ôćĺ
    12Ôćĺ## Installing mdBook
    14ÔćĺThere are several different strategies for installing mdBook.
    15ÔćĺThe particular method depends on your needs and preferences.
    16Ôćĺ
    17Ôćĺ### Pre-compiled binaries
    19ÔćĺPerhaps the easiest method is to use the pre-compiled binaries found on the [GitHub Releases page][releases].
    20ÔćĺA simple approach would be to use the popular `curl` CLI tool to download the executable:
    21Ôćĺ
      ÔćĺÔÇŽ
    39Ôćĺ### Building from source
    41ÔćĺBuilding from source will require having Rust installed.
    42ÔćĺSome services have Rust pre-installed, but if your service does not, you will need to add a step to install it.
    43Ôćĺ
      ÔćĺÔÇŽ
    67Ôćĺ## Running tests
    69ÔćĺYou may want to run tests using [`mdbook test`] every time you push a change or create a pull request.
    70ÔćĺThis can be used to validate Rust code examples in the book.
    71Ôćĺ
    72ÔćĺThis will require having Rust installed.
    73ÔćĺSome services have Rust pre-installed, but if your service does not, you will need to add a step to install it.
    74Ôćĺ
      ÔćĺÔÇŽ
    83Ôćĺ## Deploying
    85ÔćĺYou may want to automatically deploy your book.
    86ÔćĺSome may want to do this every time a change is pushed, and others may want to only deploy when a specific release is tagged.
    87Ôćĺ
    88ÔćĺYou'll also need to understand the specifics on how to push a change to your web service.
    89ÔćĺFor example, [GitHub Pages] just requires committing the output onto a specific git branch.
    90ÔćĺOther services may require using something like SSH to connect to a remote server.
      ÔćĺÔÇŽ
   100Ôćĺ### 404 handling
   102ÔćĺmdBook automatically generates a 404 page to be used for broken links.
   103ÔćĺThe default output is a file named `404.html` at the root of the book.
   104ÔćĺSome services like [GitHub Pages] will automatically use this page for broken links.
      ÔćĺÔÇŽ
for_developers/README.md
     1Ôćĺ# For developers
     3ÔćĺWhile `mdbook` is mainly used as a command line tool, you can also import the
     4Ôćĺunderlying libraries directly and use those to manage a book. It also has a fairly
     5Ôćĺflexible plugin mechanism, allowing you to create your own custom tooling and
     6Ôćĺconsumers (often referred to as *backends*) if you need to do some analysis of
     7Ôćĺthe book or render it in a different format.
     8Ôćĺ
     9ÔćĺThe *For Developers* chapters are here to show you the more advanced usage of
    10Ôćĺ`mdbook`.
    11Ôćĺ
    12ÔćĺThe two main ways a developer can hook into the book's build process is via,
    13Ôćĺ
    14Ôćĺ- [Preprocessors](preprocessors.md)
    15Ôćĺ- [Alternative Backends](backends.md)
    16Ôćĺ
    17Ôćĺ## The build process
    19ÔćĺThe process of rendering a book project goes through several steps.
    20Ôćĺ
    21Ôćĺ1. Load the book
    22Ôćĺ    - Parse the `book.toml`, falling back to the default `Config` if it doesn't
    23Ôćĺ       exist
    24Ôćĺ    - Load the book chapters into memory
    25Ôćĺ    - Discover which preprocessors/backends should be used
    26Ôćĺ2. For each backend:
    27Ôćĺ   1. Run all the preprocessors.
    28Ôćĺ   2. Call the backend to render the processed result.
    29Ôćĺ
    30Ôćĺ## Using `mdbook` as a library
    32ÔćĺThe `mdbook` binary is just a wrapper around the underlying mdBook crates,
    33Ôćĺexposing their functionality as a command-line program. If you want to
    34Ôćĺprogrammatically drive mdBook, you can use the [`mdbook-driver`] crate.
    35ÔćĺThis can be used to add your own functionality or tweak the build process.
    36Ôćĺ
    37ÔćĺThe easiest way to find out how to use the `mdbook-driver` crate is by looking at the
    38Ôćĺ[API Docs]. The top level documentation explains how one would use the
    39Ôćĺ[`MDBook`] type to load and build a book, while the [config] module gives a good
    40Ôćĺexplanation on the configuration system.
    41Ôćĺ
    42Ôćĺ[`MDBook`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/struct.MDBook.html
    43Ôćĺ[API Docs]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/
    44Ôćĺ[config]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/config/index.html
for_developers/backends.md
     1Ôćĺ# Alternative backends
     3ÔćĺA "backend" is simply a program which `mdbook` will invoke during the book
     4Ôćĺrendering process. This program is passed a JSON representation of the book and
     5Ôćĺconfiguration information via `stdin`. Once the backend receives this
     6Ôćĺinformation it is free to do whatever it wants.
     7Ôćĺ
     8ÔćĺSee [Configuring Renderers](../format/configuration/renderers.md) for more information about using backends.
     9Ôćĺ
    10ÔćĺThe community has developed several backends.
    11ÔćĺSee the [Third Party Plugins] wiki page for a list of available backends.
    12Ôćĺ
    13Ôćĺ## Setting up ÔÇŽ
    53Ôćĺ## Inspecting the book ÔÇŽ
